Comment: Also yscuque hataca /ɨskuke hataka/—both from MsM1. MsM2 has hischa nxie /hisṣa nsie/; yscuque /ɨskuke/.
Also toca /toka/ is used with negative verbs. cua /-kua/; yecua /ɨekua-/, as in, e.g., yecuzehunga /ieku-c̷̣ɨ-hu-nɣa/ 'rápido-1st p.sing.-come-future' 'I will come quickly'.
Refers to the afternoon, after midday. To be late is ityegosqua /itɨe-ɣo-skua/.

Refers to an old thing. An 'old man' is tybara /tɨβara/; tybacha /tɨβaṣa/, with dialectal variation. The <ch> was articulated in the Santa Fe dialect, which is described in the colonial grammars. Also sasia, means 'ancient'; fanzaquia 'very ancient'. Wheeler has saka.
Also, from MsM1 amuyia /amɨia/; from MsM2 amuyiaca /amɨiaka/.
Note that Lugo(1619) has qhyn /khɨn/, presumably *kɨhɨnɨ.
Also yetan asucune /ɨetan asukune/—both terms mean a full container. To have in abundance is fuyza /-βuɨc̷̣a/.
Wheeler has kuhupkua. Constenla has cuhu-pca
Wheeler has ta. Constenla has ta.
Variants occur in: MsM2 muyhyca; GdP mhuyzca; Lugo mhuyca. Wheeler has muihika. Constenla has muyhyca.
Wheeler has boza. Constenla has boza.
Wheeler has mika. Constenla has mica.
Also chichyc zona /ṣisɨ-k c̷̣ona/; ubtas zes /uβtas c̷̣es/.
Refers to a thin person. A thing is sotupqua /sotupkua/, from MsM1.

Means 'narrow' from outside perspective. Also afihista magueza /a-βihista maɣe-c̷̣a/ from MsM2. 'Narrow' from inside perspective: atyeza /a-tɨe-c̷̣a/; atye magueza /a-tɨe maɣe-c̷̣a/. Compiled from three manuscripts.
Means 'wide' from outside perspective. Also aty gue /a-tɨ ɣe/ 'wide' from inside perspective.
Also agahasyn mague /a-ɣahas-ɨn maɣe/; asuhuca gue /a-suhu-ka ɣe/.
Indicates without movement. anguac /anɣua-k/ indicates movement.

Lit. 'hand good' = 'right hand'. However, it appears that there is no exact equivalent of 'right' and 'left'. GdP gives sihic husa for right or left hand, with indication of gesturing direction, and comment: 'There is no other way'[to say it].
Wheeler suggests -wa, which occurs on items such as 'chin' kinhua.
Wheeler suggests -wa, which occurs on items such as 'chin' kinhua.
Also asa btasqua /asa -β-ta-skua/; fihiste btasqua /βihiste -β-ta-skua/; agyi btasqua /aɣɨi -β-ta-skua/; ys bzihisqua /ɨs -β-c̷̣ihi-skua/.
Also yban zebquysqua /ɨβan c̷̣ɨ-β-kɨ-skua/, both examples from MsM1.
Also agyn agyn bquysqua /a-ɣɨn a-ɣɨn -β-kɨ-skua/; bchunos bquysqua /-β-ṣunos β-kɨ-skua/; bchunoasuca /-β-ṣuno-a-suka/.
'To collect things, one here and one there' zemisqua /c̷̣ɨ-mi-skua/.
With meaning of 'quedarse'; 'permanecer' is yscuc zeguene /ɨ-sku-k c̷̣ɨ-ɣe-ne.
To be lying down, right-side up: ybcac izasqua /ɨ-β-ka-k i-c̷̣a-skua/.
Refers to putting one thing. To put several things, up to 8 or 10: pquysqua /p-kɨ-skua/. To put a multitud of things: bquysqua /β-kɨ-skua/.
Constenla has quy-pcua with derivational suffix.
See 12.030; first form is without movement, second form is with movement.
See 12.030; first form is without movement, second form is with movement.
Also -ty- /-tɨ-/; guasa- /ɣuasa-/. Adding suffix -na /-na/ means 'adverbios de quietud'. Suffix -ca /-ka/ means 'adverbios de movimiento'. See 12.080.
Also -ty- /-tɨ-/; guasa- /ɣuasa-/. Adding suffix -na /-na/ means 'adverbios de quietud'. Suffix -ca /-ka/ means 'adverbios de movimiento'. See 12.080.
Means 'beside a person'; MsM1 also has -quihyten /-kihɨ-ten/. 'Beside (things)' -cuhuena /-kuhu-e-na/ (GdP); -cuhutana /-kuhu-ta-na/ (MsM1); -cuhutena /-kuhu-te-na/ (MsM2).
Means 'beside a person'; MsM1 also has -quihyten /-kihɨ-ten/. 'Beside (things)' -cuhuena /-kuhu-e-na/ (GdP); -cuhutana /-kuhu-ta-na/ (MsM1); -cuhutena /-kuhu-te-na/ (MsM2).
Means to weigh on a scale. 'To weigh the cargo' afihizansuca /a-βihic̷̣a-n-suka/.
Also aguezac bgasqua /aɣec̷̣a-k β-ɣa-skua/; ai bgyisuca /ai-β-ɣɨi-suka/; bzasysuca /β-c̷̣asɨ-suka/.
'Tomar para sí' zuaca zebgusqua /c̷̣-uaka c̷̣ɨ-β-ɣu-skua/, in MsM1.

Refers to one person. 'To enter (many)' hui chigusqua /hui ṣiɣu-skua/; 'to enter (crowd or multitude)' hui btasqua /hui β-ta-skua/. 'To enter into something that is not a house' yc zemisqua /ɨk c̷̣ɨ-mi-skua/.

Means to get close to a place or person. Also: anguac zequysqua /anɣua-k c̷̣ɨ-kɨ-skua/; anguac zuhusqua /anɣua-k c̷̣-uhu-skua/; btequesuca /-βteke-suka/. 'To be near already' atequensuca /a-teke-n-suka/.
Also inysqua /i-nɨ-skua/, from MsM1. Also 'venir a menudo' zehusuca /c̷̣ɨ-hu-suka/. Wheeler has zexikiskua.
Refers to one person. 'To go out (many)' fac chigusqua /βak ṣiɣu-skua/; 'large crowd (multitude) to disperse' fac chibgusqua /βak ṣi-β-ɣu-skua/.
From MsM1. 'To lower something' guanbtasqua /ɣuan-β-ta-skua/; guasbzasqua /ɣuas-β-c̷̣a-skua/.
If one is 'coming', the form is ies isyquy /i-es i-sɨkɨ/.
Refers to Indian dances. 'To dance (Spanish people)' [lanzar]bquysqua.
refer to one person. 'To kneel—several' gotam chican chibisqua; gotam chican chipquysqua /ɣotam ṣikan ṣipkɨ-skua/.
AlternativeValue: ɣotam ṣikan β-c̷̣a-skua; ɣotam ṣikan itɨ-skua

Comment: refer to one person. 'To kneel—several' gotam chican chibisqua; gotam chican chipquysqua /ɣotam ṣikan ṣipkɨ-skua/.
AlternativeValue: ɣotam ṣikan β-c̷̣a-skua; ɣotam ṣikan itɨ-skua

Comment: 'To blow out candle' yc zebcusqua /-ɨkɨ c̷̣ɨ-β-ku-skua/.
Means to sink in water. Also 'sink in water' in zemisqua /in c̷̣ɨ-mi-skua/; 'sink in the earth' hichac zemisqua / hiṣa-k c̷̣ɨ-mi-skua/; 'sink in mud' isuac zemisqua /isua-k c̷̣ɨ-mi-skua/.
Active transitive verb. Intransitive verbs: achychynsuca; achyhyzynsuca /a-ṣɨhɨc̷̣ɨ-n-suka/.

In general, 'fall in (or on)' OBJECT + izasqua /i-c̷̣a-skua/. 'To fall from a high place' guan zmasqua /ɣuan c̷̣ɨ-ma-skua/; 'f. in the water' siec izasqua; siegac izasqua /sie-k i-c̷̣a-skua; sie-ɣa-k i-c̷̣a-skua/. 'Caer el agua en la labranza' siuz tac atansuca /siu-c̷̣ tak a-tan-suka/; 'hail falls' hichuaguaz atansuca /hiṣu-aɣua-c̷̣ a-tan-suka/.
Means to raise from the ground. Also, 'raise something, make it stand up' cus bzasqua; cus btasqua /kus -β-c̷̣a-skua; kus -β-ta-skua/.
In MsM1, 'subir trepando por un palo o pared lisa' ichiegosqua /i-ṣieɣo-skua/.
Means to twist with the hands. 'To twist thread (spindle)' zimne bzauasuca /c̷̣imne β-c̷̣aua-suka/; 't. cabuya or something thick' ys zemuyhyzasuca /ɨs c̷̣ɨ-mɨhɨc̷̣a-suka/.
In MsM1 also: yquy zehuscasuca /ɨkɨ c̷̣ɨ-huska-suka/. In MsM2 yquy zeguscasuca /ɨkɨ c̷̣ɨɣuska-suka/.
Also cona /kona/ 'mochilita/ mochila'. 'Net' used for hunting quyne /kɨne/.
Constenla has tyb-so, with derivational suffix.

Also guasbzasqua /ɣua-s-β-c̷̣a-skua/, in MsM1. Also 'hang some' guan zpquysqua /ɣua-n c̷̣ɨ-pkɨ-skua/; 'h. many (things)' guan zbiasqua /ɣua-n c̷̣ɨ-βia-skua/; 'h. cloaks, cloths, etc.' guate zmuysqua /ɣua-te c̷̣ɨ-mɨ-skua/; 'h. many cloths, etc.' guate biasqua /ɣua-te βia-skua/; 'h. from nail or hook' [clauos] bzasqua; zizuas bzasqua /[klaβos] β-c̷̣a-skua; c̷̣ic̷̣uas β-c̷̣a-skua/.
Translated as 'cabuya'. Also 'cabuya de paja' pquane /pkuane/.
Also quye quichpqua /kɨe kiṣpkua/. Constenla has quyne 'trunk, stem'.
Wheeler has ki; kie; ke. Constenla has quye.
Also 'flor de la savana' tutuaba /tutu-aβa/; 'flor de turma' iomgy /iom-ɣɨ. Wheeler has tutuaba.

Refers to tree leaf. Also quyeca /kɨe-ka/; quynxie /kɨ-nsie/. 'Hoja del maíz' is abquye; fica /aβ-kɨe; βika/; 'hoja de turma' iemzyquye; chuzynca /iemc̷̣ɨ-kɨe; ṣuc̷̣ɨnka; 'hoja de cualquiera planta del medio auajo' guane /ɣuane/. Constenla has quye.
Same as 'sow' 08.310; 'beget' 04.710. Constenla has xi-scua /si-skua/ with imperfective suffix.

'White maize' is fuquie pquyhyza /βukie pkɨhɨc̷̣a/; 'black m.' chyscamuy /ṣɨskamɨ/; 'yellow m' abtyba /aβtɨβa/; 'red m' sasamuy /sasamɨ/; 'm. no tan colorado' fusuamuy /βusuamɨ/; 'm. de arroz' hichuamuy /hiṣuamɨ; 'm. rojo blando' phochuba /βoṣuβa/, possibly /phoṣuβa/. Wheeler has atiba; aba. Constenla has aba.
From MsM1. GdP distinguishes: 'desgranar maíz' bcahachysuca /-β-kahaṣɨ-suka/; 'desgranar legumbres' btohotysuca /-β-tohotɨ-suka/.
From MsM1. GdP gives uba /uβa/, as a general term. Also, 'corn seed' absun /aβ-sun/; 'turma seed' iomsun /iom-sun/. Constenla has pcua.
Also quyecobse /kɨekoβse/, a small wooden shovel.
Latter form also means 'earth' 01.212. In MsM1, hischa fihista; iegui /hisṣa βihista; ieɣi/.
Latter form also means 'earth' 01.212. In MsM1, hischa fihista; iegui /hisṣa βihista; ieɣi/.
Refers to the opening, the entrance door. The exit door is gue quyhyne /ɣue kɨhɨne/.
From MsM1, preceded by a possessive.
In MsM1. In ancient times, a necklace of gold or copper: chihizaquihicha /ṣihic̷̣a-kihiṣa/.
Transitive form; means 'to dye black'; intransitive is bchyugosqua /βṣɨu-ɣo-skua/. 'To dye green or blue' chyscoc bgasqua /ṣɨsko-k β-ɣa-skua/; chyscoc bquysqua /ṣɨsko-k β-kɨ-skua/.
Intransitive verb, from MsM1. Transitive: zebxinsuca /c̷̣ɨ-βsin-suka/.
A 'long, large pepper' is pquata quybsa /pkuata kɨβsa/; 'round and large p.' nymqua quybsa /nɨmkua kɨβsa/; 'yellow p.' guapa quybsa /ɣuapa kɨβsa/; 'small p.' agua quybsa /aɣua kɨβsa/.

Also: iemuy /iemɨ/, MsM1 iomuy /iomɨ/. Other words for 'turma (potato)': 'turma amarilla' tybaiomy /tɨβa-iomɨ/; 'turma ancha' gazaiomy /ɣac̷̣a-iomɨ/; 'turma larga' quyiomy /kɨ-iomɨ/; 'turma grande' pquaseiomy /pkuase-iomɨ/; 'turma negra' funzaiomy /βunc̷̣a-iomɨ/; 'turma blanca' xieiomp /sie-iomɨ/; 'turma negra por dentro' bhosioiomy /βhosio-iomɨ/; 'turma harinosa' qhyhysaiomy /kɨkɨsa-iomɨ/; 'turma menuda' iomzaga /iom-c̷̣aɣa/.
Respectively: bread; bread of Spanish people.
Respectively: bread; bread of Spanish people.
Also bsahaquysuca /-β-sahakɨ-suka/; gahans bquysqua /ɣahans -β-kɨ-skua/; ins gahans bquysqua /ins ɣahans -β-kɨ-skua/.
Constenla has chu-scua 'to skin' with imperfective aspect suffix.
Verbal form. Also itochua bgusqua /itoṣua-β-ɣu-skua/; busua bgusqua /βusua -β-ɣu-skua/; ichyumy fac btasqua /iṣɨumɨ βak -β-ta-skua/.
Also hocu chahoquysuca /hoku ṣa-hokɨ-suka/; and 'cook in olla' bzoisuca /-β-c̷̣oi-suka/.
Also guas btasqua /ɣuas -βta-skua/; vmys zegyisuca /umɨs c̷̣ɨ-ɣɨi-suka/; guas zemenasuca /ɣuas c̷̣ɨ-mena-suka/.
Cf. 'nipple' 04.412. Constenla has chuchy-suca with imperfective aspect suffix.

Also 'rotten turmas' afutynsuca /a-βutɨn-suka/; 'rotten corn, before picking' achuzansuca /a-ṣuc̷̣an-suka/; 'rotten hay' agahachansuca /a-ɣahaṣan-suka/; apantynsuca /a-pantɨn-suka/; afutynsuca /a-βutɨn-suka/.
Verbal form, refers to ripe fruit.

Also bgysqua /-β-ɣɨ-skua/ 'eat bread, turmas, and various roots'; bcasqua /β-ka-skua/ 'eat corn, meat, cheese, fruit, and hard things'; bsosqua /-β-sos-kua/; 'eat honey, fat, salt, sauces' bgamysuca /-β-ɣamɨ-suka/ 'eat leaves and grass'; biotysuca /-β-iotɨ-suka/ 'eat mazamorra'; bgychasuca /-βɣiṣa-suka/ 'eat sugar cane'. Constenla has gyscua.
From LS; also opqua muyhyza /opkua mɨhɨc̷̣a/; opqua magueza /opkua maɣec̷̣a/.
Also achinan mague /a-ṣinan maɣe/; acain mague /a-kain maɣe/.
Verbal form. MsM1 also gives: zepinzesuca /c̷̣ɨ-p-inc̷̣e-suka/.
MsM1 defines it 'herir de punta'; also gives zebtosqua /c̷̣ɨ-βto-skua/ 'herir a la larga'.
MsM2 says no form for 'fever'; but gives the above for 'fever with chills'. GdP also gives the above, 'fever with chills, that is brought from hot country'.
Verbal form; lit. '1st PERS.SING-strong, force-NEGATIVE', (means 'I am without strength'). Also m-ṣihic̷̣a-nc̷̣a '2nd PERS.SING-strong-NEGATIVE'.
Constenla has gua-scua, suffix is the imperfective aspect.
Verbal form is bgysqua /βɣɨ-skua/. Also ys bcasqua /ɨs βka-skua/. MsM1 also has zebhysqua /c̷̣ɨ βhɨ-skua/.
Respectively: 'my life; your life'. Also eca, ika /eka, ika/ 'vida ajena'.
Respectively: 'my life; your life'. Also eca, ika /eka, ika/ 'vida ajena'.
Also muysca aiec suza /mɨska aiek suc̷̣a/; opquaz aguaia /opkua-c̷̣ aɣuaia/.
Verbal form is zgyzysuca /c̷̣ɨ-ɣɨc̷̣ɨ-suka/. Constenla has gye.
Constenla has quyby-suca with imperfective aspect suffix.
A bite, such as from a dog, is bcasqua /βka-skua/.
From LS, refers to adult penis; child's penis is nieta, nie /nieta, nie/. Both forms in LS.
From LS. MsM1 has: zine, mine /c̷̣-ine, m-ine/, 'my waist' 'your waist'.
Also fusque, fusquy /βuskɨ/, from LS and MsM2, respectively.
From MsM2. Wheeler has čue 'breast'; čuči 'suck'. Constenla has chue.
The form is assumed because of MsM1: quihique.
Wheeler has ita. Constenla has yta.
Wheeler has pkuakeba. Present-day Kogui has /kukkúba/.
LS has: gyquyn /ɣɨkɨn/; gie /ɣie/. MsM1 has: gye /ɣɨe/; geequihicha /ɣeekihiṣa/; MsM2 has: gy /ɣɨ/; gyquyn /ɣɨkɨn/.
Wheeler has pkua. Constenla has pcua.
Occurs in MsM2. In GdP, guyhica /ɣɨhika/; LS has: quihyca /kihɨka/; MsM1 has: puyhyca /pɨhɨka/. In present-day Damana: [khɨ'ka] 'mouth'. Wheeler has kihika. Constenla has quyhyca.
Wheeler has saka. Constenla has saca.
Wheeler has kuhuka. Constenla has cuhuca.
LS has: guiquyn /ɣui-kɨn/; MsM1 has: guqyn /gukɨn/.
Wheeler has opkua; upkua. Constenla has upcua.
MsM1 has oba /oβa/; LS has bique /βike/. Constenla has uba.
Constenla has zy-s-quy, 'root-stem formative-suffix (on noun and verb stems)'.
Alternative interpretation: /ɣepkue-kuɨn/. LS has: ziti /c̷̣iti/; quyn /kuɨn, kɨn/. MsM1 has: utaquyn /uta-kuɨn/.

Also GdP has: tymy /tɨmɨ/; fihista /βihista/; gepqua /ɣepkua/. In LS: 'parte superior de la espalda' puyhypa /pɨhɨpa/; 'parte inferior de la espalda' tymyfihista /tɨmɨ-βihista/; 'espalda sobre los riñones' gutaquyn /ɣuta-kuɨn/.
'Human bone' is muyscuyne /mɨskuɨne/. From MsM1 muisquequyne /mɨske-kuɨne/. Wheeler has kine; ken(e). Constenla has quyne.
In LS, and MsM1 yba /ɨβa/, also means 'body' 04.110. Wheeler has eba. Constenla has yba.
As it is in GdP (p.130); but in the dictionary, Letter B (not from original manuscript): guyhye /ɣɨhɨe/. From LS, quihye /kihɨe/. Wheeler has kihie.
Wheeler has zie. Constenla has zye.
MsM1 has hocu /hoku/ and ioque /ioke/. In GdP: ioque /ioke/ 'cuero seco o apartado para usar de él'. Wheeler has huka. Constenla has huca.
A bee from 'tierra caliente' is tochua / toṣua/.
Respectively: head louse; body louse. Wheeler has kʷe 'head louse'; kumne 'body louse'. Constenla has cue 'head louse'; cu-mne 'body louse', with derivational suffix.
Respectively: head louse; body louse. Wheeler has kʷe 'head louse'; kumne 'body louse'. Constenla has cue 'head louse'; cu-mne 'body louse', with derivational suffix.
Wheeler has wa. Constenla has gua.
From MsM1, refers to 'el pardillo'. Also fosua /βosua/, 'el negro'; tybsa /tɨβsa/, 'el colorado'. Constenla has chuhu-ca; chuhu-ta, both derivational suffixes occur frequently.
Refers to: 'el que se cría en los páramos'. 'El que se cría en las labranzas' cuhupquy /kuhupkɨ/.
MsM1 has: supquaquyn /supkuakɨn/. Wheeler has supkua.
GdP has suc /suk/; MsM1 and MsM2 have sue /sue/. In addition, three manuscripts have suc guana /suk ɣuana/ and sue guanna /sue ɣuanna/. Wheeler has sue; hue. Constenla has sue.
Wheeler has mue; ma. Constenla has my; mue.
Refers to son/ daughter of the sister, a relationship of great importance with respect to the uncle.

Refers to son/ daughter of the sister, a relationship of great importance with respect to the uncle. LS has: guabxique /ɣuaβsike/. Also LS has chuta /ṣuta/, for both nephew and niece. MsM1 limits the form to the kinship relationship with uncle.
MsM1 has chutoca /ṣutoka/; vocative form is guai /ɣuai/.
Also tybara /tɨβa-ra/, appears to be northern dialect variant.
Present-day Damana, spoken in the Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta, Colombia, has: 'gwia.
Con respecto de la hermana. Also pquyhyta /pkɨhɨta/.
The latter is vocative, form of address. Wheeler has paba; pabi.
The latter is vocative, form of address. Wheeler has paba; pabi.
Male form; female is guasgua fucha /ɣuasɣua βuṣa/. Also MsM1 has tecua; pinze /tekua; pinc̷̣e/, male child; MsM1 'female' pinze; hycaguy /pinc̷̣e; hɨkaɣɨ/. Constenla has guasgua.
MsM1 has: bahaoa /βahaoa/. Constenla has faoa /βagua/.
Also MsM1 pquihiza /pkihic̷̣a/, bright flash from fire.
Constenla has fa-gua with derivational suffix.
Wheeler has hika. Constenla has hyca.
Also MsM1 hista /hista/. A small brook is faquy /βakɨ/. Wheeler has watok; wato.
Also MsM1 hista /hista/. A small brook is faquy /βakɨ/. Wheeler has watok; wato.
Wheeler has sie. Constenla has sie.
GdP has: 'rock cave' hycata /hɨkata/; 'dirt cave' hichata /hiṣata/.
Also ubuca /uβuka/; hatacaubuca /hataka-uβuka/. Also ycatybuca /ɨkatɨβuka/; yscuque /ɨskuke/, MsM1.

Verbal form. Also fisuc agasqua /βisu-k a-ɣa-skua/. Adverbial forms: suas agasquana /sua-s a-ɣa-skua-na/; suas agaiaxin /sua-s a-ɣa-ia-sin/. fusuc agasquana /βusu-k a-ɣa-skua-na/; fusuc agaiaxin /βusu-k a-ɣa-ia-sin/.
Lit. 'smell-good'. A 'fragrant odor' is hazyn mague /hac̷̣-ɨn maɣe/ MsM1.
Lit. 'sabor bueno'; cf. 'good smelling' 15.250. 'Gustar' is zmuysysuca /c̷̣ɨ-β-ɨsɨ-suka/.
Verbal form, 'to make noise'. 'Hacer estruendo' atinansuca /a-tinan-suka/.
Verb form. A yellow thing is atyban mague /a-tɨβa-n maɣe/; tybco /tɨβ-ko/; tybaguaze /tɨβa-ɣuac̷̣e/.
To dry something: abuchuansuca /a-βuṣua-n-suka/. Constenla has suaty 'dry season'.
Verbal form. Also verb zequyhintansuca /c̷̣ɨ-kɨhɨntan-suka/ MsM1.
Verbal form. /c̷̣ɨ-pkɨkɨ-c̷̣ a-ṣu-ɨn-suka/. A happy person is apquyquy chuin mague /a-pkɨkɨ ṣu-ɨn maɣe/.
lit. 'smell', that is, the sniff-kiss, known elsewhere also.
Also es isasqua /es i-sa-skua/; es bquysqua /es β-kɨ-skua/.
Preceded by prefix and lexical item, e.g. chasienga cuhuc aguene /ṣa-sie-nɣa kuhuk a-ɣene/, lit. 1st pers.sing.-go-future, 'I desire to go'.
Also ys zebiosuca /ɨs c̷̣ɨ-β-io-suka/; ys zemicusuca /ɨs c̷̣ɨ-β-iku-suka/.
Noun forms; also chihiscago /ṣihiskaɣo/; and chihiscane /ṣihiskane/. Also verb ichichisc agosqua /i-ṣiṣis-k a-ɣo-skua/; yen a zgusqua /ie-nc̷̣a c̷̣ɨ-ɣu-skua/.
Also agotac btasqua /a-ɣota-k β-ta-skua/; ahuiche btasqua /a-huiṣe β-ta-skua/, all verb forms.
Also zepquyquyz ybtasqua /c̷̣ɨ-pkɨkɨ-c̷̣ ɨ-β-ta-skua/. MsM2 has zepuyquyz yquy btasqua /c̷̣ɨ-pɨkɨ-c̷̣ ɨkɨ β-ta-skua/.
Also zipqua bquysqua /c̷̣-ipkua β-kɨ-skua/, lit. '1st pers.sing.(?)-trans-make-present', 'imitate me'.
Also tucumzi /tukumc̷̣i/—both in MsM1 and MsM2. In GdP pqueta tucumzi 'tonto'.

AlternativeValue: c̷̣ɨ-pkɨkɨ ɨkɨ a-mi-skua; c̷̣ɨ-pkɨkɨ ɨkɨ a-c̷̣a-skua
c̷̣ɨ-pkɨkɨ ɨkɨ a-mi-skua; c̷̣ɨ-pkɨkɨ ɨkɨ a-c̷̣a-skua

Comment: Respectively: referring to past; to future.
Respectively: referring to past; to future.

Various examples: ipquan pquaca /ipkua-n pkua-ka/; ipquanzona /ipkua-nc̷̣ona/; ipqua quihichan /ipkua kihiṣan/; hac aguen /hak a-ɣen/; hac aguen nzona /hak a-ɣen nc̷̣ona/; aqhaguen npquaca /hak a-ɣen npkua-ka/.
Also ty zegusqua /tɨ c̷̣ɨ-ɣu-skua/. Constenla has ty-scua with imperfective aspect suffix.
Also chahasugue /ṣaha-su-ɣe/. Constenla has gua-scua with imperfective aspect suffix.
The Indian language is muysccubun; the Spanish l. is sucubun.
Verbal form is ahycan zemasqua; ahyca zegusqua. Wheeler has hika. Constenla has hyca.
Also caquez bquysqua /kakɨ-c̷̣ɨ β-kɨ-skua/. 'To fight in war' is zesabagoskua /c̷̣ɨ-saβa-ɣo-skua/, from MsM1.
Also 'small net' chupquasuca /ṣupkua-suka/. Constenla has quynygoscua 'to hunt with a net'.

Refers to 'caza de montería'. Also zquyngasqua /c̷̣ɨ-kɨnɣa-skua/ 'to hunt with net'; ichihi zegosqua /iṣihi c̷̣ɨ-ɣo-skua/ 'h. with lazo'; zfuntagosqua /c̷̣ɨ-βunta-ɣo-skua/ 'h. with blowgun'; zcatagosqua /c̷̣ɨ-kata-ɣo-skua/ 'h. with trap'; zefuinsuca /c̷̣ɨ-βuin-suka/ 'h. effectively, with success'.

AlternativeValue: a-ṣie c̷̣ɨ-ɣu-skua; a-ṣie c̷̣ɨ-β-ni-skua; a-ṣie c̷̣ɨ-β-c̷̣ɨ-skua
a-ṣie c̷̣ɨ-ɣu-skua; a-ṣie c̷̣ɨ-β-ni-skua; a-ṣie c̷̣ɨ-β-c̷̣ɨ-skua
a-ṣie c̷̣ɨ-ɣu-skua; a-ṣie c̷̣ɨ-β-ni-skua; a-ṣie c̷̣ɨ-β-c̷̣ɨ-skua

Comment: Introduced by the colonial clergy, lit. 'high + city, country'.
